metadata.title: Boeing-Stearman Model 75
aws::graph::propositions: Boeing-Stearman Model 75 Information
The government issued Approved Type Certificate No. 743 for the civilian version of the Boeing-Stearman Model 75.
The civilian version of the Boeing-Stearman Model 75 was designated the Model A75L3.
The Model A75L3 was also known as PT-13.
The civilian version of the Boeing-Stearman Model 75 was designated the Model A75N1.
The Model A75N1 was also known as PT-17.
About 60 Boeing-Stearman Model 75 civilian versions were sold to civilian flight schools.
Parks College of Engineering, Aviation and Technology was one of the civilian flight schools that purchased the Boeing-Stearman Model 75.
Parks College of Engineering, Aviation and Technology is a flight school.
Some Boeing-Stearman Model 75 civilian versions were sold for export.
On 15 March 1941, Boeing delivered the 1000th trainer to the Army.
On 15 March 1941, Boeing delivered the 1001st trainer to the Navy.
On 27 August 1941, Boeing delivered the 2000th trainer to the Army.
On 27 July 1944, Boeing delivered its 10,000th primary trainer.
The Boeing-Stearman Model 75 was also known as the Kaydet.
The Kaydet was a conventional biplane.
The Kaydet had rugged construction.
The Kaydet had a large, fixed tailwheel undercarriage.
The Kaydet had accommodation for the student and instructor in open cockpits.
The open cockpits in the Kaydet were arranged in tandem.

text:
government issued Approved Type Certificate No. 743 for the civilian version of the Model 75. Designated the Model A75L3 (PT-13) and Model A75N1 (PT-17), about 60 were sold to civilian flights schools such as Parks College of Engineering, Aviation and Technology, and for export.
On 15 March 1941, the company delivered the 1000th trainer to the Army, and the 1001st trainer to the Navy. Then on 27 August 1941, the company delivered the 2000th trainer to the Army. On 27 July 1944, the company delivered its 10,000th primary trainer.
The Kaydet was a conventional biplane of rugged construction, with a large, fixed tailwheel undercarriage, and accommodation for the student and instructor in open cockpits in tandem.
